en: Envelope containing the documents for the denied Cherokee Freedmen case of Henry Albert et al.
An envelope with "Henry Albert etal [sic]" handwritten at the top. Below this signature, the following is stamped: "Refused. Action approved by Secretary of Interior. Jun 21, 1904."
Department of the Interior, Commission to the Five Civilized Tribes, Fort Gibson, I. T., April 10, 1901 [Martha Albert et al. application]
Application of Martha Albert et al. for enrollment as Cherokee Freedmen
United States. Commission to the Five Civilized Tribes
Interviewer: James Davenport, T. B. Needles; Interviewees: Martha Albert, John Melton, Mandy Benton; Stenographer: M. D. Green
Filed with the following cases: D-102 (Henry Albert), D-103 (John Barnes), and D-100 (Lula Knalls).

Testimony of Martha Albert, a former enslaved African American, on her own behalf and her children for membership in the Cherokee Nation. She mentions that she lives in Tahlequah District, Oklahoma, but has been living in Sequoyah. Also includes testimonies from John Melton and nd Mandy Benton, both Cherokee Freedman. It is determined that Martha Albert appears in the "Kerns-Clifton" roll, but not in the 1880 tribal roll or the Census roll of 1896. Judgment is suspended and their names placed on a "doubtful card."

Testimony of Robert Barnes, a formerly enslaved person living in the the Sequoyah District in Oklahoma, on his own behalf, for enrollment as a Cherokee Freedman. Also includes the testimony of his uncle, Colly Albert from the Illinois Distrct, OKlahoma on his behalf, as well as the testimony of his aunt, Martha Albert from Tahlequah District, Oklahoma, on behalf of herself and her two children. According to his testimony, Robert Barnes is the son of Sam and Jennie Barnes. Jennie, the sister of Martha Albert, was a formerly enslaved person who had been enslaved by Johnson Whitmire.

Interviewer: Clifton R. Breckinridge, W. W. Hastings; Interviewees: Albert Johnson, Andy Crossland, Rose Rogers; Stenographer: M. D. Green
Filed iwith the following cases: D-102 (Henry Albert), D-103 (John Barnes), and D-100 (Lula Knalls)
Barnes and Knalls copies have "Supplemental: D 42" typewritten at the top of the first page.

Testimony of Albert Johnson, Andy Crossland, Rose Rogers on behalf of Martha Albert, a formerly enslaved person, for membership in the Cherokee Nation. Albert Johnson, from Sequoyah District, testifies that he was a former neighbor of Martha Albert. Andy Crossland, a former enslaved person and Confederate soldier from the Illinois District, testifies that he lived in Sequoyah District before the Civil War. He recalls first meeting Martha at Cale Starr's plantation near Fort Smith, Arkansas. Rose Rogers, a formerly enslaved person from Saline District, testifies that she knew Martha when they were children in Goingsnake District before the Civil War, and that Martha and her family had been enslaved by Johnson Whitmire. She also testifes spending the Civil War in the Choctaw Nation.

United States. Commission to the Five Civilized Tribes
Interviewers: A. S. McRea, W. W. Hastings, T. B. Needles; Interviewees: Ruth Hunt, Emma Finley, Harry Still; Stenographer: J. O. Rosson
Filed in the following cases: D-102 (Henry Albert et al.), D-103 (John Barnes et al.), and D-100 (Lula Knalls et al.).

Testimony of Ruth Hunt, a Cherokee Freedman from Vinita District, on behalf of Marth Albert, for membership in the Cherokee Nation. Ruth testifies that she spent the Civil War in Fort Smith, Arkansas, and that Martha's husband worked for her family in 1867 after she returned to the Cherokee Nation. Also includes the testimonies of Emma Finley, the sister of Ruth Hunt, from Tahlequah Territory, and Harry Still, a Cherokee Freedman and former enslaved person. According to his testimony, Harry Still had been previously owned by George Whitmire, the brother of Johnson Whitmire, Martha Albert's former enslaver.

Application of Martha Albert et al. for enrollment as Cherokee Freedmen
United States. Commission to the Five Civilized Tribes
Interviewers: A. S. McRea, W. W. Hastings, T. B. Needles; Interviewees: Ruth Hunt, Emma Finley, Harry Still; Stenographer: J. O. Rosson
Filed in the following cases: D-102 (Henry Albert et al.), D-103 (John Barnes et al.), and D-100 (Lula Knalls et al.).

Testimony of Ruth Hunt, a Cherokee Freedman from Vinita District, on behalf of Marth Albert, for membership in the Cherokee Nation. Ruth testifies that she spent the Civil War in Fort Smith, Arkansas, and that Martha's husband worked for her family in 1867 after she returned to the Cherokee Nation. Also includes the testimonies of Emma Finley, the sister of Ruth Hunt, from Tahlequah Territory, and Harry Still, a Cherokee Freedman and former enslaved person. According to his testimony, Harry Still had been previously owned by George Whitmire, the brother of Johnson Whitmire, Martha Albert's former enslaver.

Filed with D- 102, (Henry Albert), D-103 (John Barnes), and D-100 (Lula Knalls).

Testimony of Watt Whitmire on behalf of Martha Albert, a formerly enslaved person, for membership in the Cherokee Nation. Watt testifies that he is the son of Johnson Whitmire, Martha Albert's former enslaver. He discusses his recollections of enslaved persons living on his father's farm in Goingsnake District before the Civil War. Also includes the testimony of J.W. Alberty, a Cherokee "by blood" from Goingsnake District.. J.W. Alberty testifies about his recollection of the Whitmire family and the sale of Martha's family to a man called Dillingham from Arkansas, who allegedly later moved them to Texas.

Testimony of Sam B. Barnes, brother-in-law to Martha Albert, on her behalf for membership in the Cherokee Nation. A formerly enslaved person, he lived in Fannin County Texas before the Civil War and moved to Fort Smith after the war ended. He later migrated to the Cherokee Nation in Oklahoma, and married Martha Albert's younger sister, Jennie Boland. He also discusses the parents of Martha Albert and where they are buried.

Testimony of Aaron Whitmire, a Cherokee Freedman, on behalf of Martha Albert, a formerly enslaved person, for membership in the Cherokee Nation. Prior to the Civil War, Aaron had been enslaved by George Whitmire, the brother of Martha's owner, Johnson Whitmire, in Goingsnake District, He testifies as to whether Martha Albert and her mother Nancy had been sold to Dillingham, a man from Arkansas, who allegedly moved them to Texas. He also testifies as to whether another enslaved person with the name "Martha" had been living on the Whitmire farm at the time. Upon this additional testimony the Commission to the Five Civilized Tribes made a decision to file a motion for continuance.

Interviewer: W. W. Hastings; Interviewee: Aaron Whitmire; Stenographer: Eula Jeanes Branson
"Neal & London, attorneys for applicants; Bell, Hastings & Davenport, attorneys for the Cherokee Nation."

Testimony of Aaron Whitmire, a Cherokee Freedman, on behalf of Martha Albert, a formerly enslaved person, for membership in the Cherokee Nation. Prior to the Civil War, Aaron had been enslaved by George Whitmire, the brother of Martha's owner, Johnson Whitmire, in Goingsnake District, He testifies as to whether Martha Albert and her mother Nancy had been sold to Dillingham, a man from Arkansas, who allegedly moved them to Texas. He also testifies as to whether another enslaved person with the name "Martha" had been living on the Whitmire farm at the time. Upon this additional testimony the Commission to the Five Civilized Tribes made a decision to file a motion for continuance.
Letter from E.A. Hitchcock, Secretary of the Interior, to the Commission to the Five Civilized Tribes about Martha Albert's Cherokee Freedmen case, Washington, March 25, 1905
United States. Department of the Interior
Letter is addressed to the Commission to the Five Civlized Tribes at "Muskogree, Indian Territory."

Letter from E.A. Hitchcock, Secretary of Interior, informing the Commission that the Department has granted a motion filed by attorneys Neal and London of Fort Smith, Arkansas to re-open the case of Martha Albert et al. Although her a applicaiton for enrollment as a Cherokee Freedman was previously denied, new evidence has emerged that suggests that Johnson Whitmire may have enslaved two women named Martha" in the Goingsnake District with divergent personal histories.

Letter from T.B. Needles, the Commissioner of the Five Civilized Nations, to Neal & London from Fort Smith, Arkansas, who represented Martha Albert, a former enslaved person, in her case for membership in the Cherokee Nation. he letter informs the attorneys about the rehearing and readjudication of the Martha Albert case, scheduled for April 20, 1905, at the Commission's offices in Muskogee, Indian Territory.
